# Portolan atlas harness

When mapping, explaining, auditing, or navigating a local codebase or multi-repo
landscape:

1. Use the target-local wrappers installed under `<target-root>/.portolan/bin`.
   If they are missing, run the Portolan installer first:
   `<portolan-checkout>/scripts/portolan-install.sh <target-root> --harness cursor --bundle-dir <bundle-dir>`
2. Build the atlas bundle first:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-scan.sh <target-root> <bundle-dir> --yes --skip-install --no-viewer`
3. Remove `--skip-install` only after explicit operator approval to install
   missing local OSS tools.
4. Query the bundle at answer time with
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-bundle-query.sh`
   instead of loading the full bundle into chat.
   Start with `repos`, `relationships`, `hotspots`, and `gaps`; use `search`,
   `symbol`, and `source` for drill-down when indexes or selected paths exist.
5. Open the viewer when the user needs navigation:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-viewer.sh`.
6. Cite bundle record ids or source paths and preserve `unknown`,
   `cannot_verify`, and `not_assessed`.

Do not require `go install` unless the user asks for the legacy Go path.
